    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Per-surface walkthrough template (two-axis: discoverability + correctness)" location="(this task — used by Steps 3.1 through 3.7)">
        For each of the seven surfaces, the walkthrough has the same shape:
        1. **Discoverability prompt to operator**: "Open Spaarke Dev in a fresh
           browser session (cleared session storage). Without using any prior
           knowledge, find {surface}. Note: what cues led you to it? Was it
           obvious, partial, or hidden?"
        2. **Operator action**: exercise the surface per the discoverability path
           found.
        3. **Correctness prompt to operator**: "Now exercise {surface} through
           {N specific assertions}. For each, report pass / partial / fail."
        4. **Findings capture**: operator speaks/types observations; Claude
           Code paraphrases + assigns severity per Step 4 rubric.
        5. **Surface aggregate verdict**: operator summarizes one-line.
        6. Move to next surface.

        The seven surfaces use the same template; only the per-surface assertions
        differ (defined in Steps 3.1 through 3.7 inline).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Severity rubric (binding for ranking findings)" location="(this task — Step 4 inline)">
        - **Blocking (B)**: Contract violation, data loss, security issue,
          authentication failure, or "Phase 3 cannot ship until this is fixed".
          Stops the testing pass for immediate escalation OR is filed with
          explicit escalation in §5 of results doc.
        - **High (H)**: Major UX gap, regression vs prior shipped state, broken
          happy-path, surface-level discoverability failure (cue completely
          absent for a designed-discoverable capability). Feeds R6 backlog
          with HIGH priority; should be addressed within R6 scope.
        - **Medium (M)**: Polish gap, minor UX rough edge, partial-but-usable
          discoverability cue, edge-case correctness gap. Feeds R6 backlog;
          R6 prioritizes per available bandwidth.
        - **Low (L)**: Nice-to-have, observation-only, future-enhancement seed,
          single-user-perspective preference. Recorded but does NOT seed R6
          backlog — feeds task 044 lessons-learned doc only.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Information-leakage discipline (per ADR-018)" location="(this task — applies to all evidence capture)">
        Spaarke Dev uses synthetic data, but the discipline applies regardless:
        - Question text from operator: OK verbatim (operator's own words).
        - Response answer text from LLM: paraphrase only (e.g., "Insights
          returned a structured Predict-Matter-Cost envelope with 4
          contributing factors; structurally well-formed").
        - Citation source names from synthetic documents: OK verbatim.
        - Citation excerpt text / passage content: paraphrase only.
        - UI labels, button text, error messages: OK verbatim (these are
          product strings, not customer data).
        - CorrelationIds, tab IDs, session IDs: OK verbatim (opaque debug keys).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Discoverability cue source-of-truth (where each surface's expected entry point lives)" location="(this task — inline per surface in Step 3)">
        - Workspace switching: SwitchWorkspace dropdown in shell header (R4
          shipped); auto-install of pinned workspaces on cold load
          (`docs/architecture/SPAARKEAI-WORKSPACE-ARCHITECTURE.md`).
        - Attachment uploads: paperclip icon in `ChatInputBar`; 25 MB binary
          cap; MIME allow-list (`docs/standards/CHAT-ATTACHMENT-POLICY.md`).
        - Section picker: "+ New Workspace" button → WorkspaceLayoutWizard →
          section picker shows 7 sections including Calendar + Daily Briefing
          (R3 shipped; R4 unchanged).
        - Pane collapse: click pane header → collapses to icon-only strip;
          click strip → re-expands (R4 task 094).
        - Chat + playbook lifecycle: ConversationPane → slash command menu OR
          natural language → playbook invocation → response render →
          session persists across page reloads (R3/R4 shipped; R5 left intact).
        - W-4: in Assistant pane, after a file-related response, click "Open as
          Workspace tab" → `DocumentViewerWidget` opens in Workspace pane (R5
          task 022 dispatcher wiring).
        - W-5: in Context pane, complete a wizard (e.g., Create Project), final
          step has "Add to Workspace" button → wizard result opens as Workspace
          tab (R5 dispatcher; if R5 did NOT ship a W-5 dispatcher, mark this
          sub-surface as "still partial — concept validation tests dispatcher
          design only" and downgrade testing to design-review depth).
        - Summarize: `/summarize` slash command OR Get Started welcome card
          (task 041) OR natural-language "summarize these files" → file upload
          → `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` progressive rendering →
          `FilePreviewContextWidget` shows preview.
        - Insights tool: natural-language matter/project/invoice question OR
          `/ask-insights` slash command → `InsightsQueryToolHandler` →
          `InsightsResponseRenderer` (playbook OR RAG path) → clickable
          citations (v1.1) or display-name-only (v1.0) → confidence floor
          badge (`< 0.6` threshold).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Wave F deployment state inquiry (binding for Surface 7 design)" location="(this task — Step 2 pre-flight)">
        Before testing Surface 7 (Summarize + Insights), check
        `notes/insights-r2-coordination.md` §8 changelog for Wave F status.
        If Wave F shipped to Spaarke Dev: test v1.1 paths (SSE streaming +
        clickable `href` citations). If Wave F NOT shipped: test v1.0
        fallback paths (single-shot + display-name-only citations). Record
        which state was tested in results doc metadata. Either is
        contract-acceptable per NFR-11 — DO NOT mark a v1.0 state as a
        finding; the graceful fallback IS the design.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Cross-link findings to task 044 R6 backlog seed list" location="(this task — Step 6)">
        High + Medium findings from this task are the seed list for task 044
        (D3-05 lessons-learned + R6 backlog). In §7 of `testing-pass-results.md`,
        Claude Code produces a markdown-table seed list with: finding ID,
        surface, severity (H or M only — Low is excluded), paraphrased
        description, suggested R6 framing. Task 044 consumes this list
        directly to seed the R6 backlog section of `lessons-learned.md`.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Task 043 is the **operator-led end-to-end testing** pass that closes Phase 3
      polish. It is binding per plan.md D3-04 + spec SC-22 (lessons-learned
      produced per phase wrap-up — which task 044 produces using findings from this
      task). Without this task's evidence, Phase 3 cannot close.

      The seven surfaces under test are NOT arbitrary — they are exactly the
      kickoff doc's high-readiness list (`notes/user-testing-kickoff.md` §Q3 +
      `notes/ground-truth-spaarkeai-state.md` §7) plus the two surfaces R5
      MATERIALLY CHANGED (Summarize vertical slice from Phase 2 + Insights tool
      integration). The kickoff doc explicitly added the "now that they're real"
      qualifier for W-4/W-5 — R4 left those infrastructure-only (dispatcher gap);
      R5 task 022 (DocumentViewerWidget upgrade) shipped the W-4 dispatcher; W-5
      remained partial unless R5 extended a wizard (operator-driven scope choice
      at test time — see Step 3.6 below).

      The testing pass is **operator-led** by design. UI testing on a model-driven
      Power App + Code Page surface is intrinsically observation-heavy — most
      "discoverability" judgments are subjective and require human intuition
      ("did the cue feel obvious?"). Claude Code's role is structural: prompt
      the operator in a consistent way per surface, capture observations without
      editorializing, apply the severity rubric consistently, and compile the
      ranked findings. The operator's judgment is the source of truth; Claude's
      output is the structured artifact.

      The dependency chain matters: this task depends on 040 + 041 + 042 ALL
      shipping FIRST. Task 040 (`/analyze` configuration-only proof point)
      validates the platform-extension claim and gives the operator a fresh
      surface to test the configuration-extension story. Task 041 (Get Started
      welcome card) gives the operator a binary new discoverability cue for
      Surface 7 — does the welcome card make `/summarize` discoverable for new
      users? Task 042 (telemetry dashboards) gives the operator access to App
      Insights / Grafana panels during testing so they can observe the
      `r5.summarize.invocation` event stream + cost-per-session live as they
      test. Skipping ANY of 040/041/042 leaves the test pass incomplete.

      The Wave F state question matters specifically for Surface 7 (Insights
      tool). At time of task 043 execution, Wave F may or may not have shipped
      to Spaarke Dev — both states are contract-acceptable per NFR-11 graceful
      fallback. Test the live state and record it. Do NOT mark a v1.0 state
      as a finding — the graceful fallback IS the design.

      Severity-ranked findings flow to task 044 (lessons-learned + R6 backlog).
      Blocking findings, if any, BLOCK task 044 until resolved (the operator
      decides whether to file a hot-fix follow-up task or accept the surface
      with explicit Phase 3 ship caveats). High + Medium findings seed the R6
      backlog. Low findings are recorded in the lessons-learned doc as
      observations but do NOT seed backlog work.

      The information-leakage discipline (ADR-018) is reinforced even on
      synthetic data — train muscle memory. Question text + UI labels +
      citation source names are OK verbatim; response answer text + citation
      excerpts are paraphrased. Operator observations captured paraphrased
      (the operator's own paraphrasing of what they observed; not Claude
      Code's interpretation).

      After task 043 closes, task 044 (D3-05 lessons-learned + R6 backlog)
      runs. After 044 closes, task 090 (project wrap-up) runs. Then R5 ships.
    </background>
